{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17595942","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17595942"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:08:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:08:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15383"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15383","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15383"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.36,0.09,0.23,0.27,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8074"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61242"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8074","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8074"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15383"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46692"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4911"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"},{"type":"tags","id":"8763"},{"type":"tags","id":"9992"},{"type":"tags","id":"10333"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19596"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19598"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61242","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/61242"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ENeurogenic bowel dysfunction is a common complication following spinal cord injury that significantly impacts quality of life.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes bowel dysfunction after spinal cord injury?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["80-95% of people with spinal cord injury experience bowel dysfunction","20-30% of people with spinal cord injury experience bowel dysfunction","Injuries above T12 cause decreased anal sphincter tone","Injuries below T12 lead to increased colonic transit time","Bowel management is only required in complete spinal cord injuries"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EFollowing spinal cord injury, \u003Cstrong\u003E80-95% of people experience bowel dysfunction\u003C/strong\u003E, not \u003Cstrong\u003E20-30%\u003C/strong\u003E. The level of injury determines the type of neurogenic bowel syndrome that develops.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInjuries above T12 (upper motor neuron bowel) result in increased anal sphincter tone and slow colonic transit, not \u003Cstrong\u003Edecreased anal sphincter tone\u003C/strong\u003E. Conversely, injuries below T12 (lower motor neuron bowel) cause decreased tone and reflex activity, not \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreased colonic transit time\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBoth complete and incomplete spinal cord injuries can cause significant bowel dysfunction requiring management, so it is incorrect that \u003Cstrong\u003Ebowel management is only required in complete spinal cord injuries\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Neurogenic bowel dysfunction affects over 80% of people with spinal cord injury","Upper motor neuron bowel syndrome occurs with injuries above T12, causing increased tone and constipation","Lower motor neuron bowel syndrome occurs with injuries below T12, causing decreased tone and incontinence"],"references":["Ahuja CS, Wilson JR, Nori S, Kotter MRN, Druschel C, Curt A, Fehlings MG. Traumatic spinal cord injury. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2017 Apr 27;3:17018. doi: 10.1038/nrdp.2017.18. PMID: 28447605.","Bennett J, Das JM, Emmady PD. Spinal Cord Injuries. 2024 Mar 10. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32809556.","Lima R, Monteiro A, Salgado AJ, Monteiro S, Silva NA. Pathophysiology and Therapeutic Approaches for Spinal Cord Injury. Int J Mol Sci. 2022 Nov 10;23(22):13833. doi: 10.3390/ijms232213833. PMID: 36430308; PMCID: PMC9698625.","van den Berg ME, Castellote JM, de Pedro-Cuesta J, Mahillo-Fernandez I. Survival after spinal cord injury: a systematic review. J Neurotrauma. 2010 Aug;27(8):1517-28. doi: 10.1089/neu.2009.1138. PMID: 20486810."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46692"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15383"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46692","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/46692"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-15T11:25:17+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-15T11:26:07+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8074"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61242"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"grou